-- PRESS DIGEST - RUSSIA - July 8
-- 
-- Tue Jul 08, 2014 05:02AM EDT
-- None



MOSCOW, July 8 (Reuters) - The following are some of the leading stories in Russia's newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

VEDOMOSTI www.vedomosti.ru - Prosecutors have asked the court to sentence Sergei Udaltsov and Leonid Razvozzhayev to 8 years in jail for organising clashes with police during protests in May 2012. - The government wants to cut the amount it plans to spend on Crimea by 2020 to 790 billion roubles ($23 billion), down from 1.1 trillion roubles. The federal budget will provide 733 billion roubles and the rest is expected to come from investors, the daily says.   KOMMERSANT www.kommersant.ru - Russian oil major Rosneft <ROSN.MM> is challenging in court the decision of Sakhalin Energy to refuse it access to its pipeline. Fifty percent of Sakhalin Energy's shares belong to gas monopoly Gazprom <GAZP.MM>.   ROSSIISKAYA GAZETA www.rg.ru - Russia has conducted a further test of its new-generation surface-to-air missile system S-500 which will be able to intercept intercontinental ballistic missiles.  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA www.ng.ru - Russia earned $5.6 billion through sales of weapons and military equipment in the first six months of the year, President Vladimir Putin said on Monday. - Almost 23,000 Ukrainian citizens have recently applied for Russian citizenship and 48,206 for temporary permission to live on Russian territory, a Federal Migration Service official said on Monday.